1. Replacing $x$ with $x - 4$ shifts right 4 units. The starting 
 point of $f$ (at the origin) moves to $(4, 0)$. The domain changes 
 from $[0, \infty)$ to $[4, \infty)$.

2. Replacing $x$ with $x + 2$ shifts left 2 units. The starting 
 point moves to $(-2, 0)$. The domain changes from $[0, \infty)$ to 
 $[-2, \infty)$.

figure[H]

tikzpicture[scale=0.6]
 (-3,0) – (7,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-0.5) – (0,3) node[above] {$y$};
 plot (, {sqrt()}) 
 node[right] { $\sqrt{x}$};
 plot (, {sqrt(-4)}) 
 node[right] { $\sqrt{x-4}$};
 plot (, {sqrt(+2)}) 
 node[above] { $\sqrt{x+2}$};
 in {-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} (,0.1) – (,-0.1) node[below] {$\x$};
tikzpicture
Horizontal shifts of $f(x) = \sqrt{x}$. Gray: original, starting at origin. Teal: $\sqrt{x-4}$, shifted right 4 units, starting at $(4, 0)$. Rose: $\sqrt{x+2}$, shifted left 2 units, starting at $(-2, 0)$.

